- **Enable Auditing in Spring Boot**: Add `@EnableJpaAuditing` to your main application class.

- **Add Dependencies**: Ensure you have the following dependencies in your `pom.xml` or `build.gradle`:
  ```xml
  <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
      <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-data-jpa</artifactId>
  </dependency>
  ```

- **Define Auditing Entity**: Use `@EntityListeners(AuditingEntityListener.class)` on your entity class.

- **Create Audit Listener**: Implement `AuditorAware` to provide the current auditor (user).
  ```java
  @Service
  public class SpringSecurityAuditorAware implements AuditorAware<String> {
      @Override
      public Optional<String> getCurrentAuditor() {
          Authentication authentication = SecurityContextHolder.getContext().getAuthentication();
          if (authentication == null || !authentication.isAuthenticated()) {
              return Optional.empty();
          }
          return Optional.of(authentication.getName());
      }
  }
  ```

- **Configure Audit Properties**: Define `audit.createdBy` and `audit.updatedBy` in your `application.properties`.

- **Entity Fields for Auditing**:
  ```java
  @EntityListeners(AuditingEntityListener.class)
  public class MyEntity {
      @CreatedBy
      private String createdBy;

      @CreatedDate
      @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
      private Date createdDate;

      @LastModifiedBy
      private String lastModifiedBy;

      @LastModifiedDate
      @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
      private Date lastModifiedDate;
  }
  ```

- **Latest Version**: Spring Boot 3.0 and Spring Data JPA 2.7 are recommended for the latest features and improvements.

- **Key Config Options**:
  - `spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.envers.audit_table_suffix`: Suffix for audit tables.
  - `spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.envers.revision_type_field_name`: Name of the revision type field.

These steps provide a concrete guide to setting up auditing in your Spring Data JPA application.
